In article <gradyC5Ay1A.Gv5@netcom.com> grady@netcom.com (1016/2EF221) writes:
>
>This is true even though (to my knowledge) that empirically
>figuring out the optimal hash function (for a given input
>set compute the function that gives you NO collisions at all)
>is a non-P problem.  See Knuth.

There is, however a probabilistic algorithm for producing a
perfect hash function (one which produces no collisions and maps
N into values 0 to N-1) which is almost guaranteed to result in an
answer rather quickly.
